rectResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompressing the cheek \u003C/strong\u003Eto keep food between the teeth, is the primary function of the buccinator muscle (image). This flat muscle forms the muscular wall of the cheek and plays a crucial role during mastication by preventing food from accumulating in the oral vestibule (the space between the teeth and cheek).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options describe functions of other facial muscles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWrinkles the forehead\u003C/strong\u003E - The frontalis muscle performs this\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElevates the corners of the mouth\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by the zygomaticus major muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlares the nostrils\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by the nasalis muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECloses the eyelids\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by the orbicularis oculi muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe buccinator muscle originates from the alveolar processes of the maxilla and mandible and inserts into the orbicularis oris at the corner of the mouth. It is innervated by the buccal branches of the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The buccinator muscle forms the muscular wall of the cheek and assists in mastication by keeping food between the teeth.","The buccinator muscle is innervated by the buccal branches of the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII).","The buccinator muscle originates from the alveolar processes of the maxilla and mandible and inserts into the orbicularis oris at the corner of the mouth."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cBuccinator muscle lateral\u201d by Anatomography\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 2.1 jp Unported license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.1/jp/deed.en). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Buccinator_muscle_lateral.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63893"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18664"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21426"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21426"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TQdmNjxNjakxY62T8mLyNSIUqR1dqE.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TQdmNjxNjakxY62T8mLyNSIUqR1dqE.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":640}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63893","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63893"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T13:13:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T13:14:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11396"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78551"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attribut